Class        Range        Default Subnet Mask        Network/Host Split        Usage
A        1.0.0.0 â€“ 126.255.255.255        255.0.0.0        N.H.H.H        Large networks
B        128.0.0.0 â€“ 191.255.255.255        255.255.0.0        N.N.H.H        Medium networks
C        192.0.0.0 â€“ 223.255.255.255        255.255.255.0        N.N.N.H        Small networks
D        224.0.0.0 â€“ 239.255.255.255        â€“        Multicasting        
E        240.0.0.0 â€“ 255.255.255.255        â€“        Research/Experimental        
Note: Private IP ranges:

Class A: 10.0.0.0 â€“ 10.255.255.255

Class B: 172.16.0.0 â€“ 172.31.255.255

Class C: 192.168.0.0 â€“ 192.168.255.255

Summary of Data Flow (Sender â†’ Receiver)
Sender Side:
Application Data
 â†“
Application Layer (Protocols)
 â†“
Transport Layer â†’ TCP/UDP Segment
 â†“
Network Layer â†’ IP Packet
 â†“
Data Link Layer â†’ Frame (MAC added)
 â†“
Physical Layer â†’ Bits (sent over wire)

Receiver Side (Reverse):
Bits â†’ Frame â†’ Packet â†’ Segment â†’ Data
